Root Cause: Overly Sensitive p99 Standalone Trigger
This is a false positive caused by the OR-based trigger logic in detect_spend_regime_shift.

What happens step-by-step:
The file has 157 data rows (no injected data at all).

prepare_drift_data() splits it into:

Historical = rows 1-156 (used to build the profile)
Latest = row 157 (scored against the profile) -- line 158 in the file:
2025-12-29,840012.54,6205771,50713.44,2854987,16267.04,4015894,21977.93,1965510,11622.57,3938121,100706.08,8267789,128549.22,121.4133351,0.598407643,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0
The OOH_spend of the latest row is 128,549.22.

The p99 of the 156 historical OOH_spend values came out to 127,250.74 -- the latest value exceeds p99 by only ~1,299 (about 1%).

The z-score is 2.7486, which is below the YELLOW threshold of 3.0.

The bug is in the trigger condition:
    z_yellow = _to_float(thresholds.get('Z_OUTLIER_YELLOW')) or SPEND_REGIME_Z_YELLOW_DEFAULT
    z_red = _to_float(thresholds.get('Z_OUTLIER_RED')) or SPEND_REGIME_Z_RED_DEFAULT
    latest_row = retailer_df.iloc[-1]
    // ... channel loop ...
        yellow_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_yellow or exceeds_p99
        red_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_red or exceeds_p995
The or exceeds_p99 makes p99 exceedance a standalone trigger, independent of z-score. This means:

Even though z = 2.75 (below 3.0 = safe by z-score standards), the alert fires purely because 128,549.22 > 127,250.74 (p99).
For a dataset of ~157 rows, p99 corresponds to roughly the top 1-2 values. So if the latest row just happens to be one of the higher historical values, it gets flagged as an "anomaly" even though it's perfectly normal data.
Why this is a design flaw:
The p99 threshold is statistically meaningless for small datasets. With 156 historical rows, p99 essentially sits between the highest and second-highest value. Any new data point that lands near the historical maximum will exceed p99 -- that's expected ~1% of the time for clean data, which is too frequent for a production alert.

Recommended fix:
Change the trigger logic so p99/p995 are not standalone triggers, but instead act as severity amplifiers when combined with a minimum z-score floor. Something like:

# Only trigger if z-score alone is high enough
yellow_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_yellow
# OR if both z-score is moderately high AND p99 is exceeded (combined signal)
yellow_trigger = yellow_trigger or (abs_z_score >= z_yellow * 0.75 and exceeds_p99)
# Red severity requires z-score OR p995 (p995 is a much rarer threshold)
red_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_red or exceeds_p995
Or the simpler approach -- remove the standalone p99 trigger entirely and use p99/p995 only for severity escalation:

yellow_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_yellow
red_trigger = abs_z_score >= z_red or exceeds_p995
This way, a normal data point at z=2.75 would never trigger an alert, regardless of p99. To implement this fix, you'd need to switch to Agent mode.
